Obtaining the data in order to get the best grasp of ggplot2 and to fully understand the functionality its vital to remove data interpretation or uncertainty so we using the build-in ggplot2 data set. This packages only function is to help understand its functionality without worrying about data issues, data wrangling or importing data. The mpg data frame in ggplot2 has 234 rows of observations and 11 columned variables. To look at the data frame mpg is typed in the R console. Variables in this data frame include: 1)displ: the engine size of the cars in L 2)hwy: the cars fuel efficiency in miles/gallon (mpg) A car with low efficiency uses more petrol compared to a high efficiency car when they travel the same distance. To know more about this data set use ?mpg in console

#Load the data (mpg is built into ggplot2)

data(mpg)

Variables the mpg data frame should include: 1)displ - Which is the engine size in L 2)hwy - Which is the cars fuel efficiency in miles/L A car with a low fuel efficiency uses more fuel than a car with a high fuel efficiency when they travel the same distance.

#Create first plot Creating my first ggplot Can plot the data using (data=mpg) Put the size of the engine (displ) on the x axis Put the fuel efficiency (hwy) on the y axis

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy))

#Next section from R for data science textbook The plot shows a negative relationship between engine size (displ) and fuel efficiency (hwy). In other words, cars with big engines use more fuel. What does this say about fuel efficiency and engine size?

When the cars engine size increases the fuel efficiency decreases by approximately double.

ggplot()makes co-ordinate system that you can add layers to. The first argument of ggplot() is the data set used in the graph (data). So ggplot(data=mpg) makes an empty graph. The next step is to add layers. the geom_point() function adds layer of points to plot which makes a scatter plot. Each geom function takes a mapping argument which defines how variables in data set are mapped to visual properties.Geom is always paired with aes() and the x and y specify which variables to map on these axes. Ggplot looks for the map variables in the data argument which in this instance is mpg.

#Understanding grammar of graphics This is the graphing template and you can use this to help develop ggplot plots. ggplot(data=) + (mapping=aes())

Your ggplot code will follow a generic template seen below. You will ALWAYS: 1)Call ggplot 2)Input data 3)Provide a geom function with a collection of mappings

Learning the template will help to realize what EXACTLY needs to go into a ggplot2and how to offer input. Lets revisit this First make an empty ggplot() that simply provides the co-ordinate system that that the remainder of the ggplot2 arguments can be mapped to. Try it.

What happens if we just try to run ggplot on its own? This just created a plot window and nothing else

ggplot()

Or with just the data specified?

ggplot(data=mpg)

This also just returned an empty plot

#We need to map some aesthetics!! In addition to plotting co-ordinates x and y, you can add a third variable like class, by mapping it to an aesthetic represented by aes() which can be seen in the template above. Aesthetic can include: 1)Size 2)Shape 3)Colour When youre creating a plot, you essentially need two attributes of a plot: 1)A geom 2)Aesthetics. Can convey information about your data by mapping aesthetics in your plot to the variables in your dataset. To map an aesthetic to a variable you need to associate the name of the aesthetic to the name of the variable INSIDE aes()

#Change point colour by class

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy,colour=class))

Above have mapped class to colour but can also map to the size aesthetic in the same way.NOTE: Dont plot a variable which is not continuous to a continuous aesthetic like size.

#Change point size by class

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy,size=class))
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

Note the warning!!! WARNING: using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

#Change transparency (alpha) by class Here alpha is what dictates the transparency. If you try a simple number like 0.3 to this aesthetic it will globally change the transparency to all the
points. This is a useful tip for dense point clouds where you would want a reader to see that there are overlapping data points.

#Next section is from ggplot2 alpha reference material Alpha refers to the opacity of a geom. Values of alpha range from 0-1, with the lower values referencing to more transparent colours. Alpha can also be modified by colour or fill if either aesthetics provide colour values using an RGB specification like RRGGBBAA where AA references the transparency values.

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy,alpha=class))
## Warning: Using alpha for a discrete variable is not advised.

Another warning!! Question: When would using alpha (or size be appropriate??) Using alpha would be appropriate when: 1)Trying to visualize data 2)Highlighting data points 3)Layering data points 4)Customizing data

#Change point shape by class

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy,shape=class))

You can also set properties manually like offering a number/colour.

#Make all points blue

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy),color="blue")

There are a range of manual aesthetics that can be set to manually change appearance of plot: 1)Name of a colour as a character string 2)Size of a point in mm 3)Shape of a point as a number

What happens if try to map aesthetic to something other than a variable name like aes(colour=displ<5) When I tried this a ggplot was produced where data points were separated into teal and red colours based on whether their fuel efficiency was above 5 miles/L. If this was true the data point was teal and if this was false the data point was red. See below.

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=displ,y=hwy,colour=displ<5))

#Troubleshooting There were minor errors that appeared in the code from this point on. I will show both the wrong code and my fixed version.

Below is a purposeful mistake with the corrected version directly below it in a chunk. IN this code the + should be in top line.

ggplot(data=mpg) + geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ, y=hwy))

Like so

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy))

#Faceting and panal plots It is common practice to break single complex plots into many sub plots (panels). This allows for development of separate plots for a range of reasons. In ggplot this is done using facets. To facet a plot using 1 variable, use facet_wrap() and ~dictates which variable you want to subset data with. NOTE is for discrete variables only. #Facet_wrap Split the plot out by car type (class)

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y =hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~class,nrow=2)

#Facet_grid If you want to more than one variable use facet_grid(). Here need two variables using ~ to split them up. A separate facet for each combination of drive-type (e.g.4WD) * number of cylinders

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(drv~cyl)

Note that there are no occurrences of 5 cylinder 4WDs OR RWD vehicles! #Facet_grid by just row (or column) Use a . if you dont want to facet in row or column dimensions. See what happens below ggplot(data = mpg) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x=displ,y=hwy)) + facet_grid(.~cyl)

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(cyl ~ .)

Or alternatively you can use facet_grid(.~cyl)

ggplot(data = mpg) +   
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(.~cyl)

#Exercise: Read ?facet_wrap.

?facet_wrap
## starting httpd help server ... done

What does nrow and ncol do? These control the number of rows and columns in the plot

What other options control the layout of the individual panels? The below chunk of code changes the order in which the panels appear and changes the levels of the underlying factors

mpg$class2 <- reorder(mpg$class, mpg$displ)
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(vars(class2))

and this next chunk of code you can allow scales to vary across the panels with the scales argument. Free scales make it easier to see patterns within each panel, but it harder to compare across panels.

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ,hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(vars(class),scales="free")

#Lines Ggplot can use variety of visual objects to show your data. To show data as points use geom_point() which we have already used.

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy))

#To display the same data as a smooth line fit through the points use geom_smooth(). However, ggplot2 can use a variety of geom objects to represent the data. Here, we might want to use bar plots, line charts, boxplots and so on. Well we can handle this issue in ggplot directly using a different geom to plot the same data. Here, instead of plotting points, we will use a smooth line.

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_smooth(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

#Question:Why dont we use geom_line() here? What would that look like? We dont use geom_line() here because this package creates line plots and adds a line that goes through connecting dots. See below.

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy))

So lets recap. A geom is an object that your plot uses to represent the data. To change the geom type in your plot, simply change the geom function that you add to your plot template. Sometimes you may want to try a few things out, in which case you could use comments to help you remember what worked and what didnt.

#Using comments (#) Comments are very useful as they allow the user to keep track of the work they have done or any errors they have fixed. It also allows readers to follow their coding methodology with more precision and clarity. See below

ggplot(data= mpg) + 
  #geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy)) + #points horrible 
  geom_smooth(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy)) #try smooth line
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Question: How does R work out where to plot the line??? Can use the chunk output to inform us. Can also use the help menu.

#Changing linetype When using drv it sorts cars into 3 types based on type of car.

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_smooth(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy,linetype=drv)) 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Can also use lty = for the same result.

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_smooth(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy,lty=drv)) 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

#Grouping Using the group argument to show that the data is grouped. You can set the group aesthetic to a categorical variable to draw multiple objects.

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_smooth(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy,group=drv))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Look at ggplot2 cheat sheet for more tips.

#Change line colour based on drv value

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_smooth(
    mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy,color=drv),
    show.legend=FALSE,
  )
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

#Multiple geoms We are increasing complexity by plotting multiple geoms on a single plot. All that is needed to be done is add them together. This is a nice choice for showing the underlaying data and how it relates to the geom_smooth line. We already did this one way.

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy)) +
  geom_smooth(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Duplicating the top row means if wanted to change the x variable it would need to be changed in other areas. This is not ideal in a programming sense and can increase chance of an error so ggplot which allows for overarching mappings to its argument making them GLOBAL mappings when applied to every geom A better way

ggplot(data = mpg,mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

#Can still manipulate each geom/layer separately: Now using mappings in specific layers to enable the display of different aesthetics in different layers

ggplot(data=mpg,mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy)) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(colour=class)) + 
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Now we have different colours to indicate the raw data (geom_point) and one colour for the overall relationship (geom_smooth). Neat!

We are Specifying further using class=(subcompact)

ggplot(data=mpg,mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy)) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(color=class)) + 
  geom_smooth(data=filter(mpg,class=="subcompact"),se=FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

Question: what does the se = FALSE do? se=false makes sure the standard error bars are plotted without additional standard error bands.

#Bar plot #Next part straight from textbook On x-axis the cut is shown and on the y-axis the count is shown but count is not a variable of diamonds. Where does in come from? 1)Bar charts, histograms, and frequency polygons bin data and then plot bin counts (the number of points that fall in each bin). 2)Smoothers fit a model to your data and then plot predictions from the model. 3)Boxplots compute a robust summary of distribution and then display a specially formatted box. 

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=cut))

Algorithm to calculate the new values for a graph is called a stat and Can use geoms and stat interchangeably. Below Ive re-created a previous plot using stat_count() instead of geom_bar()

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  stat_count(mapping=aes(x=cut))

#Overriding defaults Might want to override a default stat and change the default stat (a count or summary) to identity (raw value of a variable). Tribbles is essentially a dataframe . Make some new data

demo <- tribble(
  ~cut,         ~freq,
  "Fair",       1610,
  "Good",       4906,
  "Very Good",  12082,
  "Premium",    13791,
  "Ideal",      21551
)
demo
## # A tibble: 5  2
##   cut        freq
##   <chr>     <dbl>
## 1 Fair       1610
## 2 Good       4906
## 3 Very Good 12082
## 4 Premium   13791
## 5 Ideal     21551
ggplot(data=demo) +
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=cut,y=freq),stat="identity")

Question: Why did we specify now specify a y axis? On the y axis we are plotting cut

#What if we want to know the proportion rather than the absolute frequency? We can also override a default mapping from transformed variables to aesthetics. EXAMPLE: you could display a bar chart of the PROPORTION of your total diamond dataset rather than a count

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=cut,y=stat(prop),group=1))
## Warning: `stat(prop)` was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
##  Please use `after_stat(prop)` instead.

Question: Does anyone get the warning thats in the workbook? Warning: stat(prop)` was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0. If so, can use geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut, y = stage(after_stat = prop), group = 1))

#Plotting statistical details Can also use the stat_summary argument to show more about transformations

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  stat_summary(
    mapping=aes(x=cut,y=depth),
    fun.min=min,
    fun.max=max,
    fun=median
  )

#Aesthetic adjustments adjustments Another way to boost the way you can convey information with plots using ggplot2 is to use aesthetics like colour or fill to change aspects of bar colours. We already did this once, but there are multiple options available to you, including changing the fill our outline colours.

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=cut,colour=cut))

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=cut,fill=cut))

Question: Does anyone notice anything different in the colour scheme of this plot? (Hint: Its in the viridis colour palette (colour blind friendly), but why is it different from the colour palette we used earlier?)

Check out the difference:

ggplot(data = mpg,mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy)) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(color=class)) 

ggplot(data=diamonds,mapping=aes(x=color,y=depth)) + 
  geom_point(mapping=aes(color=cut))

#Filling by a variable Now try using these aesthetics to colour by another variable like clarity. Notice how the stacking is done automatically. This is done behind the scenes with a position argument.

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=cut,fill=clarity))

#To alter transparency (alpha) Ability to make position adjustments is crucial as allows your customise plots in 4 ways: 1)Identify (raw data) Using position=identity able you to place each object EXACTLY where it in the context of the graph. This is vital for chart points (scatter) but does not work for bar plots as too much information. So in this case need to change the bar aesthetic

ggplot(data=diamonds,mapping=aes(x=cut,fill=clarity)) + 
  geom_bar(alpha=1/5,position="identity")

#To color the bar outlines with no fill color

ggplot(data=diamonds,mapping=aes(x=cut,colour=clarity)) + 
  geom_bar(fill=NA,position="identity")

#Position adjustments 2)Fill (changes heights) position=fill works like stacking, but makes each set of stacked bars the same height.

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=cut,fill=clarity),position="fill")

#Position=dodge 3)Dodge (doesnt put things on top of each other) Position=dodge places overlapping objects directly beside each other places overlapping objects directly beside one another.

ggplot(data=diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=cut,fill=clarity),position="dodge")

# Jittering 4)Jitter Position = jitter adds a small amount of random noise to each point to avoid overplotting when points overlap. This is useful for scatterplots but not barplots.

ggplot(data=mpg) + 
  #geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy),position="jitter")
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=displ,y=hwy))
